1. Real world analogy behind namespaces
Namespaces are a mechanism for partitioning resources, code, or data into logically grouped, isolated, and distinct sets to avoid naming collisions.
Why We Use Them
Avoiding Collisions: Different libraries or teams can use the same name for a variable, class, or service.
Organization: Logically organizing related resources, like grouping all data-related tools together.
Security & Isolation: Restricting access so one team’s malfunctioning application doesn't crash another team's application.

2. Control Groups(cgroups)
Control Groups(cgroups) are a fundamental Linux kernel feature.

3. Need of control groups
used to limit, account for, and isolate the resource usage (CPU, memory, disk I/O, network bandwidth, etc.) of a collection of processes

4. Types of resources controlled by cgroups
CPU: Regulates distribution of CPU cycles via weights, quotas, and bandwidth limits.
Memory: Manages memory consumption, including userland memory (page cache/anonymous memory) and swap usage.
I/O (blkio/io): Limits read/write bandwidth and latency for block devices.
PIDs: Restricts the number of tasks (processes) a group can spawn.
Devices: Controls access to specific hardware devices.
Network: Prioritizes traffic or classifies packets for network traffic control.

5. Container Image
A Docker container image is a lightweight, standalone, and executable software package that serves as a read-only template for creating Docker containers. 
It bundles everything needed to run an application consistently across any computing environment (development, testing, or production), including the application code, a runtime, system tools, libraries, and settings
